A sensor measuring and reporting the monetary cost of the electrical energy billed to a site or facility.
The amount of electrical energy billed to a site or facility, typically represented in kilowatt-hours (kWh).
A device to read biometric information from a part of the body such as a fingerprint or an iris.

An event in a calendar

Canadian Regional Median Total Emissions refer to the median of Total Emissions calculated for all comparable properties within a specified region of Canada (e.g., a territory or province).
Canadian Regional Median Total GHG Emissions Intensity refers to the median measure of total CO2 imissions intensity within a specified region of Canada (e.g., a territory or province).

Chilled Water System GHG Emissions Factor is a specific type of Emissions Factor used for properties employing chilled water systems. It converts the energy consumed by these systems into equivalent GHG emissions.
The history of wireless access points to which the current device is connected.
A type of lock that can be electronically controlled.
Report the cost-related parameters within a system.
A device model of devices.

Direct Fuels System GHG Emissions Factor is a specific type of Emissions Factor used for properties employing systems that directly burn fuels (e.g., natural gas or fuel oil). It converts the energy consumed by these systems into equivalent GHG emissions.
Direct Emissions are emissions associated with onsite fuel combustion (e.g. combustion of natural gas or fuel oil).
Measures direct greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions per area or energy unit.
Measures direct greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions per unit area, such as square meter.
The number of distinct pixels in each dimension that can be displayed. It is quoted as as width x height.

The email address as an identity of an Email Account.

The ENERGY STAR Score is a measure of how well a property is performing relative to similar properties, when normalized for climate and operational characteristics.
The calculated value of energy consumption over a specific period.
It’s calculated by dividing the total energy consumed by the building in one year (measured in kBtu or GJ) by the total gross floor area of the building (measured in square feet or square meters)
A side of an Opening from a direction. E.g., An opening where a door is located, there can be two entries from each directions (spaces) to the door.
Temporal occurrences.

Greenhouse Gas (GHG) Emissions refer to the amount of key greenhouse gases, including carbon dioxide (CO2), methane (CH4), and nitrous oxide (N2O), released into the atmosphere by a particular source.
The Emissions Factor is a coefficient that converts the energy consumption of a given fuel type into equivalent GHG emissions.
Measures greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions per area or energy unit.
Measures greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions per area, such as square meter.
Measures greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions per energy unit, such as kilowatt-hour.
A gate is a point of entry into a space usually within an opening in a fence. Or as a 'free standing' gate.
An alarm indicating if the door is held open after normally opened.

Hot Water System GHG Emissions Factor is a specific type of Emissions Factor used for properties employing hot water systems. It converts the energy consumed by these systems into equivalent GHG emissions.
Indirect Emissions are emissions associated with purchases of electricity, district steam, district hot water, or district chilled water.
Measures indirect greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions (from off-site energy sources) per area or energy unit.
Measures indirect greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions from off-site sources per unit area, such as square meter.
An invite to a certain event or an area.
Median of Total Emissions in a specified area (Country, Region, etc).

screen orientation whose values are either `Landscape` or `Portrait`.

The annual amount of all the energy your property consumes on-site, regardless of the source. It includes energy purchased from the grid or in bulk (which are the amounts on utility bills), as well as renewable energy generated and consumed on-site such as from solar and wind (excess renewable energy generated on-site and sold to the utility is excluded from site energy use)
